  "doi": "10.1038/ni.2206",
  "title": "Structural basis for the killing of human beta cells by CD8(+) T cells in type 1 diabetes.",
  "journal": "Nature immunology",
  "year": 2012,
  "authors": "Bulek AM, Cole DK, Skowera A, Dolton G, Gras S, Madura F, Fuller A, Miles JJ, Gostick E, Price DA, Drijfhout JW, Knight RR, Huang GC, Lissin N, Molloy PE, Wooldridge L, Jakobsen BK, Rossjohn J, Peakman M, Rizkallah PJ, Sewell AK."
 },
 "executive_summary": "This study determined the crystal structure of the autoreactive TCR 1E6 bound to HLA-A*0201 presenting a glucose-sensitive preproinsulin peptide, the antigen recognized by CD8+ T cells that kill insulin-producing beta cells in type 1 diabetes. The 1E6-pMHCI interaction exhibited unusually weak binding affinity despite rigid, lock-and-key engagement, driven by peptide-centric recognition through an aromatic-cap motif in the CDR3 loops with minimal contacts to the MHC class I surface itself. This structural mode\u2014highly focused on peptide while making suboptimal overall TCR-pMHCI contacts\u2014provides a mechanistic explanation for how an autoreactive TCR can escape negative selection in the thymus and subsequently mediate pathogenic recognition of self-antigen. The findings illuminate how weakly binding, peptide-focused TCRs can nonetheless drive autoimmune beta-cell destruction in type 1 diabetes, offering insights into the structural basis of autoimmune CD8+ T cell reactivity.",
 "noncanonical": {
